# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phylogenetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Bayesian inference refers to a probabilistic method developed by Reverend Thomas Bayes based on Bayes' theorem.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Published posthumously in 1763 it was the first expression of inverse probability and the basis of Bayesian inference.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Independently, unaware of Bayes' work, Pierre-Simon Laplace developed Bayes' theorem in 1774.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Bayesian inference or the inverse probability method was the standard approach in statistical thinking until the early 1900s before RA Fisher developed what's now known as the classical/frequentist/Fisherian inference.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Computational difficulties and philosophical objections had prevented the widespread adoption of the Bayesian approach until the 1990s, when Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithms revolutionized Bayesian computation.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The Bayesian approach to phylogenetic reconstruction combines the prior probability of a tree P(A) with the likelihood of the data (B) to produce a posterior probability distribution on trees P(A|B).
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The posterior probability of a tree will be the probability that the tree is correct, given the prior, the data, and the correctness of the likelihood model.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MCMC methods can be described in three steps: first using a stochastic mechanism a new state for the Markov chain is proposed.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Secondly, the probability of this new state to be correct is calculated.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Thirdly, a new random variable (0,1) is proposed.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] If this new value is less than the acceptance probability the new state is accepted and the state of the chain is updated.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This process is run thousands or millions of times.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The number of times a single tree is visited during the course of the chain is an approximation of its posterior probability.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Some of the most common algorithms used in MCMC methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithms, the Metropolis-Coupling MCMC (MC³) and the LOCAL algorithm of Larget and Simon.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] One of the most common MCMC methods used is the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, a modified version of the original Metropolis algorithm.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It is a widely used method to sample randomly from complicated and multi-dimensional distribution probabilities.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] A neighbour tree, Tj, is selected from the collection of trees.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] If R ≥ 1, Tj is accepted as the current tree.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] If R < 1, Tj is accepted as the current tree with probability R, otherwise Ti is kept.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] At this point the process is repeated from Step 2 N times.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The algorithm keeps running until it reaches an equilibrium distribution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It also assumes that the probability of proposing a new tree Tj when we are at the old tree state Ti, is the same probability of proposing Ti when we are at Tj.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] When this is not the case Hastings corrections are applied.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The aim of Metropolis-Hastings algorithm is to produce a collection of states with a determined distribution until the Markov process reaches a stationary distribution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Movement of the chain to state j with probability αi,j and remains in i with probability 1 – αi,j.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Metropolis-coupled MCMC algorithm (MC³) has been proposed to solve a practical concern of the Markov chain moving across peaks when the target distribution has multiple local peaks, separated by low valleys, are known to exist in the tree space.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This is the case during heuristic tree search under maximum parsimony (MP), maximum likelihood (ML), and minimum evolution (ME) criteria, and the same can be expected for stochastic tree search using MCMC.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This problem will result in samples not approximating correctly to the posterior density.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The (MC³) improves the mixing of Markov chains in presence of multiple local peaks in the posterior density.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It runs multiple (m) chains in parallel, each for n iterations and with different stationary distributions $\pi _{j}(.)\$ , $j=1,2,\ldots ,m\$ , where the first one, $\pi _{1}=\pi \$ is the target density, while $\pi _{j}\$ , $j=2,3,\ldots ,m\$ are chosen to improve mixing.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] so that the first chain is the cold chain with the correct target density, while chains $2,3,\ldots ,m$ are heated chains.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Note that raising the density $\pi (.)$ to the power $1/T\$ with $T>1\$ has the effect of flattening out the distribution, similar to heating a metal.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] In such a distribution, it is easier to traverse between peaks (separated by valleys) than in the original distribution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] After each iteration, a swap of states between two randomly chosen chains is proposed through a Metropolis-type step.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] At the end of the run, output from only the cold chain is used, while those from the hot chains are discarded.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Heuristically, the hot chains will visit the local peaks rather easily, and swapping states between chains will let the cold chain occasionally jump valleys, leading to better mixing.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] However, if $\pi _{i}(\theta )/\pi _{j}(\theta )\$ is unstable, proposed swaps will seldom be accepted.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This is the reason for using several chains which differ only incrementally.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] An obvious disadvantage of the algorithm is that $m\$ chains are run and only one chain is used for inference.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] For this reason, $\mathrm {MC} ^{3}\$ is ideally suited for implementation on parallel machines, since each chain will in general require the same amount of computation per iteration.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The LOCAL algorithms offers a computational advantage over previous methods and demonstrates that a Bayesian approach is able to assess uncertainty computationally practical in larger trees.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The LOCAL algorithm is an improvement of the GLOBAL algorithm presented in Mau, Newton and Larget (1999) in which all branch lengths are changed in every cycle.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The LOCAL algorithms modifies the tree by selecting an internal branch of the tree at random.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The nodes at the ends of this branch are each connected to two other branches.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Imagine taking these three selected edges and stringing them like a clothesline from left to right, where the direction (left/right) is also selected at random.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The two endpoints of the first branch selected will have a sub-tree hanging like a piece of clothing strung to the line.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The algorithm proceeds by multiplying the three selected branches by a common random amount, akin to stretching or shrinking the clothesline.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Finally the leftmost of the two hanging sub-trees is disconnected and reattached to the clothesline at a location selected uniformly at random.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Suppose we began by selecting the internal branch with length $t_{8}\$ that separates taxa $A\$ and $B\$ from the rest.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Suppose also that we have (randomly) selected branches with lengths $t_{1}\$ and $t_{9}\$ from each side, and that we oriented these branches.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] To estimate a branch length t of a 2-taxon tree under JC, in which $n_{1}$ sites are unvaried and $n_{2}$ are variable, assume exponential prior distribution with rate $\lambda \$ .
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The density is $p(t)=\lambda e^{-\lambda t}\$ .
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] where $U\$ is uniformly distributed between $-w\$ and $w\$ .
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] We will compare results for two values of $w\$ , $w=0.1\$ and $w=0.5\$ .
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] In each case, we will begin with an initial length of $5\$ and update the length $2000\$ times.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] There are many approaches to reconstructing phylogenetic trees, each with advantages and disadvantages, and there is no straightforward answer to "what is the best method?".
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Maximum parsimony (MP) and maximum likelihood (ML) are traditional methods widely used for the estimation of phylogenies and both use character information directly, as Bayesian methods do.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Maximum Parsimony recovers one or more optimal trees based on a matrix of discrete characters for a certain group of taxa and it does not require a model of evolutionary change.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MP gives the most simple explanation for a given set of data, reconstructing a phylogenetic tree that includes as few changes across the sequences as possible.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The support of the tree branches is represented by bootstrap percentage.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] For the same reason that it has been widely used, its simplicity, MP has also received criticism and has been pushed into the background by ML and Bayesian methods.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MP presents several problems and limitations.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] For morphological data, recent simulation studies suggest that parsimony may be less accurate than trees built using Bayesian approaches, potentially due to overprecision, although this has been disputed.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Studies using novel simulation methods have demonstrated that differences between inference methods result from the search strategy and consensus method employed, rather than the optimization used.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] As in maximum parsimony, maximum likelihood will evaluate alternative trees.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] However it considers the probability of each tree explaining the given data based on a model of evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] In this case, the tree with the highest probability of explaining the data is chosen over the other ones.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] In other words, it compares how different trees predict the observed data.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The introduction of a model of evolution in ML analyses presents an advantage over MP as the probability of nucleotide substitutions and rates of these substitutions are taken into account, explaining the phylogenetic relationships of taxa in a more realistic way.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] An important consideration of this method is the branch length, which parsimony ignores, with changes being more likely to happen along long branches than short ones.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This approach might eliminate long branch attraction and explain the greater consistency of ML over MP.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Although considered by many to be the best approach to inferring phylogenies from a theoretical point of view, ML is computationally intensive and it is almost impossible to explore all trees as there are too many.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Bayesian inference also incorporates a model of evolution and the main advantages over MP and ML are that it is computationally more efficient than traditional methods, it quantifies and addresses the source of uncertainty and is able to incorporate complex models of evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MrBayes is a free software tool that performs Bayesian inference of phylogeny.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Huelsenbeck and Frederik Ronquist in 2001.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] As Bayesian methods increased in popularity, MrBayes became one of the software of choice for many molecular phylogeneticists.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It is offered for Macintosh, Windows, and UNIX operating systems and it has a command-line interface.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The program uses the standard MCMC algorithm as well as the Metropolis coupled MCMC variant.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MrBayes reads aligned matrices of sequences (DNA or amino acids) in the standard NEXUS format.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MrBayes uses MCMC to approximate the posterior probabilities of trees.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The user can change assumptions of the substitution model, priors and the details of the MC³ analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It also allows the user to remove and add taxa and characters to the analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The program includes, among several nucleotide models, the most standard model of DNA substitution, the 4x4 also called JC69, which assumes that changes across nucleotides occur with equal probability.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It also implements a number of 20x20 models of amino acid substitution, and codon models of DNA substitution.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It offers different methods for relaxing the assumption of equal substitutions rates across nucleotide sites.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MrBayes is also able to infer ancestral states accommodating uncertainty to the phylogenetic tree and model parameters.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] MrBayes 3 was a completely reorganized and restructured version of the original MrBayes.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] The main novelty was the ability of the software to accommodate heterogeneity of data sets.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This new framework allows the user to mix models and take advantages of the efficiency of Bayesian MCMC analysis when dealing with different type of data (e.g. protein, nucleotide, and morphological).
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It uses the Metropolis-Coupling MCMC by default.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This version allows the users to run multiple analyses in parallel.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] It also provides faster likelihood calculations and allow these calculations to be delegated to graphics processing unites (GPUs).
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Version 3.2 provides wider outputs options compatible with FigTree and other tree viewers.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] This table includes some of the most common phylogenetic software used for inferring phylogenies under a Bayesian framework.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Some of them do not use exclusively Bayesian methods.
[src:phylogenetics/bayesian-inference-in-phylogeny] Bayesian Inference has extensively been used by molecular phylogeneticists for a wide number of applications.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Many forms of molecular phylogenetics are closely related to and make extensive use of sequence alignment in constructing and refining phylogenetic trees, which are used to classify the evolutionary relationships between homologous genes represented in the genomes of divergent species.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The phylogenetic trees constructed by computational methods are unlikely to perfectly reproduce the evolutionary tree that represents the historical relationships between the species being analyzed.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The historical species tree may also differ from the historical tree of an individual homologous gene shared by those species.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Phylogenetic trees can be either *rooted* or *unrooted* depending on the input data and the algorithm used.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A rooted tree is a directed graph that explicitly identifies a most recent common ancestor (MRCA), usually an input sequence that is not represented in the input.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Genetic distance measures can be used to plot a tree with the input sequences as leaf nodes and their distances from the root proportional to their genetic distance from the hypothesized MRCA.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Identification of a root usually requires the inclusion in the input data of at least one outgroup known to be only distantly related to the sequences of interest.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] By contrast, unrooted trees plot the distances and relationships between input sequences without making assumptions regarding their descent.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] An unrooted tree can always be produced from a rooted tree, but a root cannot usually be placed on an unrooted tree without additional data on divergence rates, such as the assumption of the molecular clock hypothesis.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The set of all possible phylogenetic trees for a given group of input sequences can be conceptualized as a discretely defined multidimensional tree space through which search paths can be traced by optimization algorithms.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Although counting the total number of trees for a nontrivial number of input sequences can be complicated by variations in the definition of a tree topology, it is always true that there are more rooted than unrooted trees for a given number of inputs and choice of parameters.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Both rooted and unrooted phylogenetic trees can be further generalized to rooted or unrooted phylogenetic networks, which allow for the modeling of evolutionary phenomena such as hybridization or horizontal gene transfer.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The basic problem in morphological phylogenetics is the assembly of a matrix representing a mapping from each of the taxa being compared to representative measurements for each of the phenotypic characteristics being used as a classifier.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The types of phenotypic data used to construct this matrix depend on the taxa being compared; for individual species, they may involve measurements of average body size, lengths or sizes of particular bones or other physical features, or even behavioral manifestations.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Of course, since not every possible phenotypic characteristic could be measured and encoded for analysis, the selection of which features to measure is a major inherent obstacle to the method.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The decision of which traits to use as a basis for the matrix necessarily represents a hypothesis about which traits of a species or higher taxon are evolutionarily relevant.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Morphological studies can be confounded by examples of convergent evolution of phenotypes.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A major challenge in constructing useful classes is the high likelihood of inter-taxon overlap in the distribution of the phenotype's variation.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Some phenotypic classifications, particularly those used when analyzing very diverse groups of taxa, are discrete and unambiguous; classifying organisms as possessing or lacking a tail, for example, is straightforward in the majority of cases, as is counting features such as eyes or vertebrae.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, the most appropriate representation of continuously varying phenotypic measurements is a controversial problem without a general solution.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This results in an easily manipulated data set but has been criticized for poor reporting of the basis for the class definitions and for sacrificing information compared to methods that use a continuous weighted distribution of measurements.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Because morphological data is extremely labor-intensive to collect, whether from literature sources or from field observations, reuse of previously compiled data matrices is not uncommon, although this may propagate flaws in the original matrix into multiple derivative analyses.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The problem of character coding is very different in molecular analyses, as the characters in biological sequence data are immediate and discretely defined - distinct nucleotides in DNA or RNA sequences and distinct amino acids in protein sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, defining homology can be challenging due to the inherent difficulties of multiple sequence alignment.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For a given gapped MSA, several rooted phylogenetic trees can be constructed that vary in their interpretations of which changes are mutations versus ancestral characters, and which events are insertion mutations or deletion mutations.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For example, given only a pairwise alignment with a gap region, it is impossible to determine whether one sequence bears an insertion mutation or the other carries a deletion.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The problem is magnified in MSAs with unaligned and nonoverlapping gaps.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In practice, sizable regions of a calculated alignment may be discounted in phylogenetic tree construction to avoid integrating noisy data into the tree calculation.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A tree built on a single gene as found in different organisms (orthologs) may not show sufficient phylogenetic signal for drawing strong conclusions.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Adding more genes by concatenating their respective multiple sequence alignments into a "supermatrix", effectively creating a huge virtual gene with more evolutionary changes available for tree inference.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This naive method only works well on genes with similar evolutionary histories; for more complex cases (organellar+nuclear datasets or joint amino acid+nucleotide alignments), some algorithms allow for informing them where each gene starts and ends (data partitioning).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Alternatively, one can infer several single-gene trees and combine them into a supertree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] With the advent of phylogenomics, hundreds of genes may be analyzed at once.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Distance-matrix methods of phylogenetic analysis explicitly rely on a measure of "genetic distance" between the sequences being classified, and therefore, they require an MSA as an input.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Distance is often defined as the fraction of mismatches at aligned positions, with gaps either ignored or counted as mismatches.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Distance methods attempt to construct an all-to-all matrix from the sequence query set describing the distance between each sequence pair.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] From this is constructed a phylogenetic tree that places closely related sequences under the same interior node and whose branch lengths closely reproduce the observed distances between sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Distance-matrix methods may produce either rooted or unrooted trees, depending on the algorithm used to calculate them.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] They are frequently used as the basis for progressive and iterative types of multiple sequence alignments.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The main disadvantage of distance-matrix methods is their inability to efficiently use information about local high-variation regions that appear across multiple subtrees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Neighbor-joining methods apply general cluster analysis techniques to sequence analysis using genetic distance as a clustering metric.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The simple neighbor-joining method produces unrooted trees, but it does not assume a constant rate of evolution (i.e., a molecular clock) across lineages.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The Fitch–Margoliash method uses a weighted least squares method for clustering based on genetic distance.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Closely related sequences are given more weight in the tree construction process to correct for the increased inaccuracy in measuring distances between distantly related sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The distances used as input to the algorithm must be normalized to prevent large artifacts in computing relationships between closely related and distantly related groups.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This correction is done through the use of a substitution matrix such as that derived from the Jukes-Cantor model of DNA evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The distance correction is only necessary in practice when the evolution rates differ among branches.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Another modification of the algorithm can be helpful, especially in case of concentrated distances (please refer to concentration of measure phenomenon and curse of dimensionality): that modification, described in, has been shown to improve the efficiency of the algorithm and its robustness.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The least-squares criterion applied to these distances is more accurate but less efficient than the neighbor-joining methods.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] An additional improvement that corrects for correlations between distances that arise from many closely related sequences in the data set can also be applied at increased computational cost.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Finding the optimal least-squares tree with any correction factor is NP-complete, so heuristic search methods like those used in maximum-parsimony analysis are applied to the search through tree space.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Independent information about the relationship between sequences or groups can be used to help reduce the tree search space and root unrooted trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Standard usage of distance-matrix methods involves the inclusion of at least one outgroup sequence known to be only distantly related to the sequences of interest in the query set.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This usage can be seen as a type of experimental control.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] If the outgroup has been appropriately chosen, it will have a much greater genetic distance and thus a longer branch length than any other sequence, and it will appear near the root of a rooted tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Choosing an appropriate outgroup requires the selection of a sequence that is moderately related to the sequences of interest; too close a relationship defeats the purpose of the outgroup and too distant adds noise to the analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Care should also be taken to avoid situations in which the species from which the sequences were taken are distantly related, but the gene encoded by the sequences is highly conserved across lineages.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Horizontal gene transfer, especially between otherwise divergent bacteria, can also confound outgroup usage.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Maximum parsimony (MP) is a method of identifying the potential phylogenetic tree that requires the smallest total number of evolutionary events to explain the observed sequence data.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Some ways of scoring trees also include a "cost" associated with particular types of evolutionary events and attempt to locate the tree with the smallest total cost.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This is a useful approach in cases where not every possible type of event is equally likely - for example, when particular nucleotides or amino acids are known to be more mutable than others.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most naive way of identifying the most parsimonious tree is simple enumeration - considering each possible tree in succession and searching for the tree with the smallest score.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Most such methods involve a steepest descent-style minimization mechanism operating on a tree rearrangement criterion.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The branch and bound algorithm is a general method used to increase the efficiency of searches for near-optimal solutions of NP-hard problems first applied to phylogenetics in the early 1980s.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Branch and bound is particularly well suited to phylogenetic tree construction because it inherently requires dividing a problem into a tree structure as it subdivides the problem space into smaller regions.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Identifying a good bound is the most challenging aspect of the algorithm's application to phylogenetics.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A simple way of defining the bound is a maximum number of assumed evolutionary changes allowed per tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A set of criteria known as Zharkikh's rules severely limit the search space by defining characteristics shared by all candidate "most parsimonious" trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The two most basic rules require the elimination of all but one redundant sequence (for cases where multiple observations have produced identical data) and the elimination of character sites at which two or more states do not occur in at least two species.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Under ideal conditions these rules and their associated algorithm would completely define a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The Sankoff-Morel-Cedergren algorithm was among the first published methods to simultaneously produce an MSA and a phylogenetic tree for nucleotide sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The imputed sequences at the interior nodes of the tree are scored and summed over all the nodes in each possible tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The lowest-scoring tree sum provides both an optimal tree and an optimal MSA given the scoring function.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Because the method is highly computationally intensive, an approximate method in which initial guesses for the interior alignments are refined one node at a time.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Both the full and the approximate version are in practice calculated by dynamic programming.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] More recent phylogenetic tree/MSA methods use heuristics to isolate high-scoring, but not necessarily optimal, trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The MALIGN method uses a maximum-parsimony technique to compute a multiple alignment by maximizing a cladogram score, and its companion POY uses an iterative method that couples the optimization of the phylogenetic tree with improvements in the corresponding MSA.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, the use of these methods in constructing evolutionary hypotheses has been criticized as biased due to the deliberate construction of trees reflecting minimal evolutionary events.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This, in turn, has been countered by the view that such methods should be seen as heuristic approaches to find the trees that maximize the amount of sequence similarity that can be interpreted as homology.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The maximum likelihood method uses standard statistical techniques for inferring probability distributions to assign probabilities to particular possible phylogenetic trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The method requires a substitution model to assess the probability of particular mutations; roughly, a tree that requires more mutations at interior nodes to explain the observed phylogeny will be assessed as having a lower probability.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This is broadly similar to the maximum-parsimony method, but maximum likelihood allows additional statistical flexibility by permitting varying rates of evolution across both lineages and sites.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In fact, the method requires that evolution at different sites and along different lineages must be statistically independent.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Maximum likelihood is thus well suited to the analysis of distantly related sequences, but it is believed to be computationally intractable to compute due to its NP-hardness.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The pruning algorithm, a variant of dynamic programming, is often used to reduce the search space by efficiently calculating the likelihood of subtrees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The method calculates the likelihood for each site in a linear manner, starting at a node whose only descendants are leaves (that is, the tips of the tree) and working backwards toward the bottom node in nested sets.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, the trees produced by the method are only rooted if the substitution model is irreversible, which is not generally true of biological systems.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The search for the maximum-likelihood tree also includes a branch length optimization component that is difficult to improve upon algorithmically; general global optimization tools such as the Newton–Raphson method are often used.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Some tools that use maximum likelihood to infer phylogenetic trees from variant allelic frequency data (VAFs) include AncesTree and CITUP.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Bayesian inference can be used to produce phylogenetic trees in a manner closely related to the maximum likelihood methods.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The choice of prior distribution is a point of contention among users of Bayesian-inference phylogenetics methods.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The use of Bayesian methods in phylogenetics has been controversial, largely due to incomplete specification of the choice of move set, acceptance criterion, and prior distribution in published work.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Bayesian methods are generally held to be superior to parsimony-based methods; they can be more prone to long-branch attraction than maximum likelihood techniques, although they are better able to accommodate missing data.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Whereas likelihood methods find the tree that maximizes the probability of the data, a Bayesian approach recovers a tree that represents the most likely clades, by drawing on the posterior distribution.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, estimates of the posterior probability of clades (measuring their 'support') can be quite wide of the mark, especially in clades that aren't overwhelmingly likely.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] As such, other methods have been put forwards to estimate posterior probability.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Some tools that use Bayesian inference to infer phylogenetic trees from variant allelic frequency data (VAFs) include Canopy, EXACT, and PhyloWGS.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Molecular phylogenetics methods rely on a defined substitution model that encodes a hypothesis about the relative rates of mutation at various sites along the gene or amino acid sequences being studied.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] At their simplest, substitution models aim to correct for differences in the rates of transitions and transversions in nucleotide sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The use of substitution models is necessitated by the fact that the genetic distance between two sequences increases linearly only for a short time after the two sequences diverge from each other (alternatively, the distance is linear only shortly before coalescence).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The longer the amount of time after divergence, the more likely it becomes that two mutations occur at the same nucleotide site.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Simple genetic distance calculations will thus undercount the number of mutation events that have occurred in evolutionary history.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The extent of this undercount increases with increasing time since divergence, which can lead to the phenomenon of long branch attraction, or the misassignment of two distantly related but convergently evolving sequences as closely related.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The maximum parsimony method is particularly susceptible to this problem due to its explicit search for a tree representing a minimum number of distinct evolutionary events.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] All substitution models assign a set of weights to each possible change of state represented in the sequence.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most common model types are implicitly reversible because they assign the same weight to, for example, a G>C nucleotide mutation as to a C>G mutation.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The simplest possible model, the Jukes-Cantor model, assigns an equal probability to every possible change of state for a given nucleotide base.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The rate of change between any two distinct nucleotides will be one-third of the overall substitution rate.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] More advanced models distinguish between transitions and transversions.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most general possible time-reversible model, called the GTR model, has six mutation rate parameters.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] An even more generalized model known as the general 12-parameter model breaks time-reversibility, at the cost of much additional complexity in calculating genetic distances that are consistent among multiple lineages.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] One possible variation on this theme adjusts the rates so that overall GC content - an important measure of DNA double helix stability - varies over time.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Models may also allow for the variation of rates with positions in the input sequence.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most obvious example of such variation follows from the arrangement of nucleotides in protein-coding genes into three-base codons.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A less hypothesis-driven example that does not rely on ORF identification simply assigns to each site a rate randomly drawn from a predetermined distribution, often the gamma distribution or log-normal distribution.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Finally, a more conservative estimate of rate variations known as the covarion method allows autocorrelated variations in rates, so that the mutation rate of a given site is correlated across sites and lineages.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most common method of model selection is the likelihood ratio test (LRT), which produces a likelihood estimate that can be interpreted as a measure of "goodness of fit" between the model and the input data.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, care must be taken in using these results, since a more complex model with more parameters will always have a higher likelihood than a simplified version of the same model, which can lead to the naive selection of models that are overly complex.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For this reason model selection computer programs will choose the simplest model that is not significantly worse than more complex substitution models.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A significant disadvantage of the LRT is the necessity of making a series of pairwise comparisons between models; it has been shown that the order in which the models are compared has a major effect on the one that is eventually selected.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] An alternative model selection method is the Akaike information criterion (AIC), formally an estimate of the Kullback–Leibler divergence between the true model and the model being tested.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] It can be interpreted as a likelihood estimate with a correction factor to penalize overparameterized models.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The AIC is calculated on an individual model rather than a pair, so it is independent of the order in which models are assessed.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A related alternative, the Bayesian information criterion (BIC), has a similar basic interpretation but penalizes complex models more heavily.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Determining the most suitable model for phylogeny reconstruction constitutes a fundamental step in numerous evolutionary studies.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, various criteria for model selection are leading to debate over which criterion is preferable.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] It has recently been shown that, when topologies and ancestral sequence reconstruction are the desired output, choosing one criterion over another is not crucial.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Instead, using the most complex nucleotide substitution model, GTR+I+G, leads to similar results for the inference of tree topology and ancestral sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A non traditional way of evaluating the phylogenetic tree is to compare it with clustering result.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] One can use a Multidimensional Scaling technique, so called Interpolative Joining to do dimensionality reduction to visualize the clustering result for the sequences in 3D, and then map the phylogenetic tree onto the clustering result.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A better tree usually has a higher correlation with the clustering result.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] As with all statistical analysis, the estimation of phylogenies from character data requires an evaluation of confidence.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A number of methods exist to test the amount of support for a phylogenetic tree, either by evaluating the support for each sub-tree in the phylogeny (nodal support) or evaluating whether the phylogeny is significantly different from other possible trees (alternative tree hypothesis tests).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most common method for assessing tree support is to evaluate the statistical support for each node on the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Typically, a node with very low support is not considered valid in further analysis, and visually may be collapsed into a polytomy to indicate that relationships within a clade are unresolved.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Many methods for assessing nodal support involve consideration of multiple phylogenies.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The consensus tree summarizes the nodes that are shared among a set of trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In a strict consensus, only nodes found in every tree are shown, and the rest are collapsed into an unresolved polytomy.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Less conservative methods, such as the majority-rule consensus tree, consider nodes that are supported by a given percentage of trees under consideration (such as at least 50%).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For example, in maximum parsimony analysis, there may be many trees with the same parsimony score.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A strict consensus tree would show which nodes are found in all equally parsimonious trees, and which nodes differ.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Consensus trees are also used to evaluate support on phylogenies reconstructed with Bayesian inference (see below).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In statistics, the bootstrap is a method for inferring the variability of data that has an unknown distribution using pseudoreplications of the original data.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For example, given a set of 100 data points, a pseudoreplicate is a data set of the same size (100 points) randomly sampled from the original data, with replacement.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] That is, each original data point may be represented more than once in the pseudoreplicate, or not at all.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Statistical support involves evaluation of whether the original data has similar properties to a large set of pseudoreplicates.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In phylogenetics, bootstrapping is conducted using the columns of the character matrix.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Each pseudoreplicate contains the same number of species (rows) and characters (columns) randomly sampled from the original matrix, with replacement.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] A phylogeny is reconstructed from each pseudoreplicate, with the same methods used to reconstruct the phylogeny from the original data.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For each node on the phylogeny, the nodal support is the percentage of pseudoreplicates containing that node.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The statistical rigor of the bootstrap test has been empirically evaluated using viral populations with known evolutionary histories, finding that 70% bootstrap support corresponds to a 95% probability that the clade exists.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, this was tested under ideal conditions (e.g. no change in evolutionary rates, symmetric phylogenies).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In practice, values above 70% are generally supported and left to the researcher or reader to evaluate confidence.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Nodes with support lower than 70% are typically considered unresolved.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Jackknifing in phylogenetics is a similar procedure, except the columns of the matrix are sampled without replacement.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Pseudoreplicates are generated by randomly subsampling the data—for example, a "10% jackknife" would involve randomly sampling 10% of the matrix many times to evaluate nodal support.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Reconstruction of phylogenies using Bayesian inference generates a posterior distribution of highly probable trees given the data and evolutionary model, rather than a single "best" tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The trees in the posterior distribution generally have many different topologies.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] When the input data is variant allelic frequency data (VAF), the tool EXACT can compute the probabilities of trees exactly, for small, biologically relevant tree sizes, by exhaustively searching the entire tree space.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Most Bayesian inference methods utilize a Markov-chain Monte Carlo iteration, and the initial steps of this chain are not considered reliable reconstructions of the phylogeny.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Trees generated early in the chain are usually discarded as burn-in.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The most common method of evaluating nodal support in a Bayesian phylogenetic analysis is to calculate the percentage of trees in the posterior distribution (post-burn-in) which contain the node.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The statistical support for a node in Bayesian inference is expected to reflect the probability that a clade really exists given the data and evolutionary model.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Therefore, the threshold for accepting a node as supported is generally higher than for bootstrapping.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Bremer support counts the number of extra steps needed to contradict a clade.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] These measures each have their weaknesses.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For example, smaller or larger clades tend to attract larger support values than mid-sized clades, simply as a result of the number of taxa in them.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Bootstrap support can provide high estimates of node support as a result of noise in the data rather than the true existence of a clade.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Ultimately, there is no way to measure whether a particular phylogenetic hypothesis is accurate or not, unless the true relationships among the taxa being examined are already known (which may happen with bacteria or viruses under laboratory conditions).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The best result an empirical phylogeneticist can hope to attain is a tree with branches that are well supported by the available evidence.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Certain characters are more likely to evolve convergently than others; logically, such characters should be given less weight in the reconstruction of a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Weights in the form of a model of evolution can be inferred from sets of molecular data, so that maximum likelihood or Bayesian methods can be used to analyze them.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For molecular sequences, this problem is exacerbated when the taxa under study have diverged substantially.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] As time since the divergence of two taxa increase, so does the probability of multiple substitutions on the same site, or back mutations, all of which result in homoplasies.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For morphological data, unfortunately, the only objective way to determine convergence is by the construction of a tree – a somewhat circular method.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Even so, weighting homoplasious characters does indeed lead to better-supported trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In general, organisms can inherit genes in two ways: vertical gene transfer and horizontal gene transfer.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] There have also been well-documented cases of horizontal gene transfer between eukaryotes.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Horizontal gene transfer has complicated the determination of phylogenies of organisms, and inconsistencies in phylogeny have been reported among specific groups of organisms depending on the genes used to construct evolutionary trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The only way to determine which genes have been acquired vertically and which horizontally is to parsimoniously assume that the largest set of genes that have been inherited together have been inherited vertically; this requires analyzing a large number of genes.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] The basic assumption underlying the mathematical model of cladistics is a situation where species split neatly in bifurcating fashion.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] While such an assumption may hold on a larger scale (bar horizontal gene transfer, see above), speciation is often much less orderly.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Research since the cladistic method was introduced has shown that hybrid speciation, once thought rare, is in fact quite common, particularly in plants.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Also paraphyletic speciation is common, making the assumption of a bifurcating pattern unsuitable, leading to phylogenetic networks rather than trees.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Introgression can also move genes between otherwise distinct species and sometimes even genera, complicating phylogenetic analysis based on genes.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This phenomenon can contribute to "incomplete lineage sorting" and is thought to be a common phenomenon across a number of groups.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In species level analysis this can be dealt with by larger sampling or better whole genome analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Often the problem is avoided by restricting the analysis to fewer, not closely related specimens.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Owing to the development of advanced sequencing techniques in molecular biology, it has become feasible to gather large amounts of data (DNA or amino acid sequences) to infer phylogenetic hypotheses.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] For example, it is not rare to find studies with character matrices based on whole mitochondrial genomes (~16,000 nucleotides, in many animals).
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, simulations have shown that it is more important to increase the number of taxa in the matrix than to increase the number of characters, because the more taxa there are, the more accurate and more robust is the resulting phylogenetic tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] This may be partly due to the breaking up of long branches.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Morphological characters that sample a continuum may contain phylogenetic signal, but are hard to code as discrete characters.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Several methods have been used, one of which is gap coding, and there are variations on gap coding.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] If more taxa are added to the analysis, the gaps between taxa may become so small that all information is lost.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Generalized gap coding works around that problem by comparing individual pairs of taxa rather than considering one set that contains all of the taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] In general, the more data that are available when constructing a tree, the more accurate and reliable the resulting tree will be.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Missing data are no more detrimental than simply having fewer data, although the impact is greatest when most of the missing data are in a small number of taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Concentrating the missing data across a small number of characters produces a more robust tree.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Because many characters involve embryological, or soft-tissue or molecular characters that (at best) hardly ever fossilize, and the interpretation of fossils is more ambiguous than that of living taxa, extinct taxa almost invariably have higher proportions of missing data than living ones.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] However, despite these limitations, the inclusion of fossils is invaluable, as they can provide information in sparse areas of trees, breaking up long branches and constraining intermediate character states; thus, fossil taxa contribute as much to tree resolution as modern taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/computational-phylogenetics] Fossils can also constrain the age of lineages and thus demonstrate how consistent a tree is with the stratigraphic record; stratocladistics incorporates age information into data matrices for phylogenetic analyses.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In phylogenetics and computational phylogenetics, **maximum parsimony** is an optimality criterion under which the phylogenetic tree that minimizes the total number of character-state changes (or minimizes the cost of differentially weighted character-state changes) is constructed.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Under the maximum-parsimony criterion, the optimal tree will minimize the amount of homoplasy (i.e., convergent evolution, parallel evolution, and evolutionary reversals).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In other words, under this criterion, the shortest possible tree that explains the data is considered best.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some of the basic ideas behind maximum parsimony were presented by James S.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Maximum parsimony is an intuitive and simple criterion, and it is popular for this reason.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, although it is easy to *score* a phylogenetic tree (by counting the number of character-state changes), there is no algorithm to quickly *generate* the most-parsimonious tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Instead, the most-parsimonious tree must be sought in "tree space" (i.e., amongst all possible trees).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For a small number of taxa (i.e., fewer than nine) it is possible to do an exhaustive search, in which every possible tree is scored, and the best one is selected.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For nine to twenty taxa, it will generally be preferable to use branch-and-bound, which is also guaranteed to return the best tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For greater numbers of taxa, a heuristic search must be performed.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In addition, maximum parsimony is not statistically consistent.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] That is, it is not guaranteed to produce the true tree with high probability, given sufficient data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As demonstrated in 1978 by Joe Felsenstein, maximum parsimony can be inconsistent under certain conditions, such as long-branch attraction.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] On the other hand, ardent cladists support the use of maximum parsimony.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Brower argues that whether a tree is wrong is fundamentally untestable, unlike the question of whether a tree is the shortest among examined ones.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In phylogenetics, parsimony is mostly interpreted as favoring the trees that minimize the amount of evolutionary change required (see for example ).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Alternatively, phylogenetic parsimony can be characterized as favoring the trees that maximize explanatory power by minimizing the number of observed similarities that cannot be explained by inheritance and common descent.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] While evolution is not an inherently parsimonious process, centuries of scientific experience lend support to the aforementioned principle of parsimony (Occam's razor).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Namely, the supposition of a simpler, more parsimonious chain of events is preferable to the supposition of a more complicated, less parsimonious chain of events.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Hence, parsimony (*sensu lato*) is typically sought in inferring phylogenetic trees, and in scientific explanation generally.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Parsimony is part of a class of character-based tree estimation methods which use a matrix of discrete phylogenetic characters and character states to infer one or more optimal phylogenetic trees for a set of taxa, commonly a set of species or reproductively isolated populations of a single species.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These methods operate by evaluating candidate phylogenetic trees according to an explicit optimality criterion; the tree with the most favorable score is taken as the best hypothesis of the phylogenetic relationships of the included taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Maximum parsimony is used with most kinds of phylogenetic data; until recently, it was the only widely used character-based tree estimation method used for morphological data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Inferring phylogenies is not a trivial problem.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A huge number of possible phylogenetic trees exist for any reasonably sized set of taxa; for example, a mere ten species gives over two million possible unrooted trees.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These possibilities must be searched to find a tree that best fits the data according to the optimality criterion.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, the data themselves do not lead to a simple, arithmetic solution to the problem.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Ideally, we would expect the distribution of whatever evolutionary characters (such as phenotypic traits or alleles) to directly follow the branching pattern of evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Thus we could say that if two organisms possess a shared character, they should be more closely related to each other than to a third organism that lacks this character (provided that character was not present in the last common ancestor of all three, in which case it would be a symplesiomorphy).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] We would predict that bats and monkeys are more closely related to each other than either is to an elephant, because male bats and monkeys possess external testicles, which elephants lack.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, we cannot say that bats and monkeys are more closely related to one another than they are to whales, though the two have external testicles absent in whales, because we believe that the males in the last common ancestral species of the three had external testicles.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, the phenomena of convergent evolution, parallel evolution, and evolutionary reversals (collectively termed *homoplasy*) add an unpleasant wrinkle to the problem of inferring phylogeny.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For a number of reasons, two organisms can possess a trait inferred to have not been present in their last common ancestor: If we naively took the presence of this trait as evidence of a relationship, we would infer an incorrect tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Empirical phylogenetic data may include substantial homoplasy, with different parts of the data suggesting sometimes very different relationships.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Methods used to estimate phylogenetic trees are explicitly intended to resolve the conflict within the data by picking the phylogenetic tree that is the best fit to all the data overall, accepting that some data simply will not fit.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It is often mistakenly believed that parsimony assumes that convergence is rare; in fact, even convergently derived characters have some value in maximum-parsimony-based phylogenetic analyses, and the prevalence of convergence does not systematically affect the outcome of parsimony-based methods.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Data that do not fit a tree perfectly are not simply "noise", they can contain relevant phylogenetic signal in some parts of a tree, even if they conflict with the tree overall.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In the whale example given above, the lack of external testicles in whales is homoplastic: It reflects a return to the condition inferred to have been present in ancient ancestors of mammals, whose testicles were internal.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This inferred similarity between whales and ancient mammal ancestors is in conflict with the tree we accept based on the weight of other characters, since it implies that the mammals with external testicles should form a group excluding whales.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, among the whales, the reversal to internal testicles actually correctly associates the various types of whales (including dolphins and porpoises) into the group Cetacea.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Still, the determination of the best-fitting tree—and thus which data do not fit the tree—is a complex process.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Maximum parsimony is one method developed to do this.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The input data used in a maximum parsimony analysis is in the form of "characters" for a range of taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There is no generally agreed-upon definition of a phylogenetic character, but operationally a character can be thought of as an attribute, an axis along which taxa are observed to vary.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These attributes can be physical (morphological), molecular, genetic, physiological, or behavioral.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The only widespread agreement on characters seems to be that variation used for character analysis should reflect heritable variation.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Whether it must be directly heritable, or whether indirect inheritance (e.g., learned behaviors) is acceptable, is not entirely resolved.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Each character is divided into discrete character states, into which the variations observed are classified.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Character states are often formulated as descriptors, describing the condition of the character substrate.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For example, the character "eye color" might have the states "blue" and "brown." Characters can have two or more states (they can have only one, but these characters lend nothing to a maximum parsimony analysis, and are often excluded).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Coding characters for phylogenetic analysis is not an exact science, and there are numerous complicating issues.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Typically, taxa are scored with the same state if they are more similar to one another in that particular attribute than each is to taxa scored with a different state.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is not straightforward when character states are not clearly delineated or when they fail to capture all of the possible variation in a character.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] How would one score the previously mentioned character for a taxon (or individual) with hazel eyes?
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Ambiguities in character state delineation and scoring can be a major source of confusion, dispute, and error in phylogenetic analysis using character data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Note that, in the above example, "eyes: present; absent" is also a possible character, which creates issues because "eye color" is not applicable if eyes are not present.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For such situations, a "?" ("unknown") is scored, although sometimes "X" or "-" (the latter usually in sequence data) are used to distinguish cases where a character cannot be scored from a case where the state is simply unknown.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Current implementations of maximum parsimony generally treat unknown values in the same manner: the reasons the data are unknown have no particular effect on analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Effectively, the program treats a ? as if it held the state that would involve the fewest extra steps in the tree (see below), although this is not an explicit step in the algorithm.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Thus, character scoring is rarely ambiguous, except in cases where sequencing methods fail to produce a definitive assignment for a particular sequence position.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Sequence gaps are sometimes treated as characters, although there is no consensus on how they should be coded.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Characters can be treated as unordered or ordered.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For a binary (two-state) character, this makes little difference.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For a multi-state character, unordered characters can be thought of as having an equal "cost" (in terms of number of "evolutionary events") to change from any one state to any other; complementarily, they do not require passing through intermediate states.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Ordered characters have a particular sequence in which the states must occur through evolution, such that going between some states requires passing through an intermediate.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This can be thought of complementarily as having different costs to pass between different pairs of states.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In the eye-color example above, it is possible to leave it unordered, which imposes the same evolutionary "cost" to go from brown-blue, green-blue, green-hazel, etc.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Alternatively, it could be ordered brown-hazel-green-blue; this would normally imply that it would cost two evolutionary events to go from brown-green, three from brown-blue, but only one from brown-hazel.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This can also be thought of as requiring eyes to evolve through a "hazel stage" to get from brown to green, and a "green stage" to get from hazel to blue, etc.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For many characters, it is not obvious if and how they should be ordered.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] On the contrary, for characters that represent discretization of an underlying continuous variable, like shape, size, and ratio characters, ordering is logical, and simulations have shown that this improves ability to recover correct clades, while decreasing the recovering of erroneous clades.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There is a lively debate on the utility and appropriateness of character ordering, but no consensus.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some authorities order characters when there is a clear logical, ontogenetic, or evolutionary transition among the states (for example, "legs: short; medium; long").
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some accept only some of these criteria.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some run an unordered analysis, and order characters that show a clear order of transition in the resulting tree (which practice might be accused of circular reasoning).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some authorities refuse to order characters at all, suggesting that it biases an analysis to require evolutionary transitions to follow a particular path.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It is also possible to apply differential weighting to individual characters.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is usually done relative to a "cost" of 1.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Thus, some characters might be seen as more likely to reflect the true evolutionary relationships among taxa, and thus they might be weighted at a value 2 or more; changes in these characters would then count as two evolutionary "steps" rather than one when calculating tree scores (see below).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There has been much discussion in the past about character weighting.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Most authorities now weight all characters equally, although exceptions are common.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For example, allele frequency data is sometimes pooled in bins and scored as an ordered character.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In these cases, the character itself is often downweighted so that small changes in allele frequencies count less than major changes in other characters.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Also, the third codon position in a coding nucleotide sequence is particularly labile, and is sometimes downweighted, or given a weight of 0, on the assumption that it is more likely to exhibit homoplasy.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In some cases, repeated analyses are run, with characters reweighted in inverse proportion to the degree of homoplasy discovered in the previous analysis (termed successive weighting); this is another technique that might be considered circular reasoning.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Character state changes can also be weighted individually.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is often done for nucleotide sequence data; it has been empirically determined that certain base changes (A-C, A-T, G-C, G-T, and the reverse changes) occur much less often than others (A-G, C-T, and their reverse changes).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These changes are therefore often weighted more.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As shown above in the discussion of character ordering, ordered characters can be thought of as a form of character state weighting.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some systematists prefer to exclude characters known to be, or suspected to be, highly homoplastic or that have a large number of unknown entries ("?").
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As noted below, theoretical and simulation work has demonstrated that this is likely to sacrifice accuracy rather than improve it.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is also the case with characters that are variable in the terminal taxa: theoretical, congruence, and simulation studies have all demonstrated that such polymorphic characters contain significant phylogenetic information.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The time required for a parsimony analysis (or any phylogenetic analysis) is proportional to the number of taxa (and characters) included in the analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Also, because more taxa require more branches to be estimated, more uncertainty may be expected in large analyses.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Because data collection costs in time and money often scale directly with the number of taxa included, most analyses include only a fraction of the taxa that could have been sampled.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Indeed, some authors have contended that four taxa (the minimum required to produce a meaningful unrooted tree) are all that is necessary for accurate phylogenetic analysis, and that more characters are more valuable than more taxa in phylogenetics.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This has led to a raging controversy about taxon sampling.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Empirical, theoretical, and simulation studies have led to a number of dramatic demonstrations of the importance of adequate taxon sampling.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Most of these can be summarized by a simple observation: a phylogenetic data matrix has dimensions of characters *times* taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Doubling the number of taxa doubles the amount of information in a matrix just as surely as doubling the number of characters.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Each taxon represents a new sample for every character, but, more importantly, it (usually) represents a new *combination* of character states.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These character states can not only determine where that taxon is placed on the tree, they can inform the entire analysis, possibly causing different relationships among the remaining taxa to be favored by changing estimates of the pattern of character changes.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The most disturbing weakness of parsimony analysis, that of long-branch attraction (see below) is particularly pronounced with poor taxon sampling, especially in the four-taxon case.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is a well-understood case in which additional character sampling may not improve the quality of the estimate.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As taxa are added, they often break up long branches (especially in the case of fossils), effectively improving the estimation of character state changes along them.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Because of the richness of information added by taxon sampling, it is even possible to produce highly accurate estimates of phylogenies with hundreds of taxa using only a few thousand characters.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Although many studies have been performed, there is still much work to be done on taxon sampling strategies.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Because of advances in computer performance, and the reduced cost and increased automation of molecular sequencing, sample sizes overall are on the rise, and studies addressing the relationships of hundreds of taxa (or other terminal entities, such as genes) are becoming common.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Of course, this is not to say that adding characters is not also useful; the number of characters is increasing as well.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Some systematists prefer to exclude taxa based on the number of unknown character entries ("?") they exhibit, or because they tend to "jump around" the tree in analyses (i.e., they are "wildcards").
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Although these taxa may generate more most-parsimonious trees (see below), methods such as agreement subtrees and reduced consensus can still extract information on the relationships of interest.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It has been observed that inclusion of more taxa tends to lower overall support values (bootstrap percentages or decay indices, see below).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The cause of this is clear: as additional taxa are added to a tree, they subdivide the branches to which they attach, and thus dilute the information that supports that branch.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] While support for individual branches is reduced, support for the overall relationships is actually increased.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Consider analysis that produces the following tree: (fish, (lizard, (whale, (cat, monkey)))).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Within error, it may be impossible to determine any of these animals' relationships relative to one another.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] To cope with this problem, agreement subtrees, reduced consensus, and double-decay analysis seek to identify supported relationships (in the form of "n-taxon statements," such as the four-taxon statement "(fish, (lizard, (cat, whale)))") rather than whole trees.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] If the goal of an analysis is a resolved tree, as is the case for comparative phylogenetics, these methods cannot solve the problem.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, if the tree estimate is so poorly supported, the results of any analysis derived from the tree will probably be too suspect to use anyway.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A maximum parsimony analysis runs in a very straightforward fashion.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Trees are scored according to the degree to which they imply a parsimonious distribution of the character data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The most parsimonious tree for the dataset represents the preferred hypothesis of relationships among the taxa in the analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Trees are scored (evaluated) by using a simple algorithm to determine how many "steps" (evolutionary transitions) are required to explain the distribution of each character.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A step is, in essence, a change from one character state to another, although with ordered characters some transitions require more than one step.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Contrary to popular belief, the algorithm does not explicitly assign particular character states to nodes (branch junctions) on a tree: the fewest steps can involve multiple, equally costly assignments and distributions of evolutionary transitions.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] What is optimized is the total number of changes.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There are many more possible phylogenetic trees than can be searched exhaustively for more than eight taxa or so.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A number of algorithms are therefore used to search among the possible trees.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Many of these involve taking an initial tree (usually the favored tree from the last iteration of the algorithm), and perturbing it to see if the change produces a higher score.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The trees resulting from parsimony search are unrooted: They show all the possible relationships of the included taxa, but they lack any statement on relative times of divergence.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A particular branch is chosen to root the tree by the user.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This branch is then taken to be outside all the other branches of the tree, which together form a monophyletic group.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This imparts a sense of relative time to the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Incorrect choice of a root can result in incorrect relationships on the tree, even if the tree is itself correct in its unrooted form.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Parsimony analysis often returns a number of equally most-parsimonious trees (MPTs).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A large number of MPTs is often seen as an analytical failure, and is widely believed to be related to the number of missing entries ("?") in the dataset, characters showing too much homoplasy, or the presence of topologically labile "wildcard" taxa (which may have many missing entries).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Numerous theoretical and simulation studies have demonstrated that highly homoplastic characters, characters and taxa with abundant missing data, and "wildcard" taxa contribute to the analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Although excluding characters or taxa may appear to improve resolution, the resulting tree is based on less data, and is therefore a less reliable estimate of the phylogeny (unless the characters or taxa are non informative, see safe taxonomic reduction).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Today's general consensus is that having multiple MPTs is a valid analytical result; it simply indicates that there is insufficient data to resolve the tree completely.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In many cases, there is substantial common structure in the MPTs, and differences are slight and involve uncertainty in the placement of a few taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There are a number of methods for summarizing the relationships within this set, including consensus trees, which show common relationships among all the taxa, and pruned agreement subtrees, which show common structure by temporarily pruning "wildcard" taxa from every tree until they all agree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Reduced consensus takes this one step further, by showing all subtrees (and therefore all relationships) supported by the input trees.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Even if multiple MPTs are returned, parsimony analysis still basically produces a point-estimate, lacking confidence intervals of any sort.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This has often been levelled as a criticism, since there is certainly error in estimating the most-parsimonious tree, and the method does not inherently include any means of establishing how sensitive its conclusions are to this error.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Several methods have been used to assess support.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Jackknifing and bootstrapping, well-known statistical resampling procedures, have been employed with parsimony analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The jackknife, which involves resampling without replacement ("leave-one-out") can be employed on characters or taxa; interpretation may become complicated in the latter case, because the variable of interest is the tree, and comparison of trees with different taxa is not straightforward.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The bootstrap, resampling with replacement (sample x items randomly out of a sample of size x, but items can be picked multiple times), is only used on characters, because adding duplicate taxa does not change the result of a parsimony analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The bootstrap is much more commonly employed in phylogenetics (as elsewhere); both methods involve an arbitrary but large number of repeated iterations involving perturbation of the original data followed by analysis.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The resulting MPTs from each analysis are pooled, and the results are usually presented on a 50% Majority Rule Consensus tree, with individual branches (or nodes) labelled with the percentage of bootstrap MPTs in which they appear.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This "bootstrap percentage" (which is not a P-value, as is sometimes claimed) is used as a measure of support.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Technically, it is supposed to be a measure of repeatability, the probability that that branch (node, clade) would be recovered if the taxa were sampled again.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Experimental tests with viral phylogenies suggest that the bootstrap percentage is not a good estimator of repeatability for phylogenetics, but it is a reasonable estimator of accuracy.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In fact, it has been shown that the bootstrap percentage, as an estimator of accuracy, is biased, and that this bias results on average in an underestimate of confidence (such that as little as 70% support might really indicate up to 95% confidence).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, the direction of bias cannot be ascertained in individual cases, so assuming that high values bootstrap support indicate even higher confidence is unwarranted.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Another means of assessing support is Bremer support, or the decay index which is a parameter of a given data set, rather than an estimate based on pseudoreplicated subsamples, as are the bootstrap and jackknife procedures described above.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Bremer support (also known as branch support) is simply the difference in number of steps between the score of the MPT(s), and the score of the most parsimonious tree that does *not* contain a particular clade (node, branch).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It can be thought of as the number of steps you have to add to lose that clade; implicitly, it is meant to suggest how great the error in the estimate of the score of the MPT must be for the clade to no longer be supported by the analysis, although this is not necessarily what it does.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Branch support values are often fairly low for modestly-sized data sets (one or two steps being typical), but they often appear to be proportional to bootstrap percentages.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As data matrices become larger, branch support values often continue to increase as bootstrap values plateau at 100%.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Thus, for large data matrices, branch support values may provide a more informative means to compare support for strongly-supported branches.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, interpretation of decay values is not straightforward, and they seem to be preferred by authors with philosophical objections to the bootstrap (although many morphological systematists, especially paleontologists, report both).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Double-decay analysis is a decay counterpart to reduced consensus that evaluates the decay index for all possible subtree relationships (n-taxon statements) within a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Maximum parsimony is an epistemologically straightforward approach that makes few mechanistic assumptions, and is popular for this reason.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, it may not be statistically consistent under certain circumstances.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Consistency in this context means that given increasing amounts of data, a method can only come closer to the correct answer – a desirable property of statistical methods.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As demonstrated in 1978 by Joe Felsenstein, maximum parsimony can be inconsistent under certain conditions.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The category of situations in which this is known to occur is called *long branch attraction*, and occurs, for example, where there are long branches (a high level of substitutions) for two characters (A & C), but short branches for another two (B & D).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A and B diverged from a common ancestor, as did C and D.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Assume for simplicity that we are considering a single binary character (it can either be + or -).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Because the distance from B to D is small, in the vast majority of all cases, B and D will be the same.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Here, we will assume that they are both + (+ and - are assigned arbitrarily and swapping them is only a matter of definition).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] If this is the case, there are four remaining possibilities.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A and C can both be +, in which case all taxa are the same and all the trees have the same length.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] A can be + and C can be -, in which case only one character is different, and we cannot learn anything, as all trees have the same length.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The only remaining possibility is that A and C are both -.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In this case, however, the evidence suggests that A and C group together, and B and D together.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As a consequence, if the "true tree" is a tree of this type, the more data we collect (i.e. the more characters we study), the more the evidence will support the wrong tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Long branch attraction was originally described in datasets where individual taxa have very different rates of evolution (heterotachy).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It was later shown that in five or more taxa, it can happen without variation in rates of evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] With even bigger trees, inconsistent can show up even when all edges of the tree have the same expected number of changes.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] When distance values are adjusted for multiple hits in a nonlinear way, it appears possible to make maximum parsimony consistent.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Supporters of maximum parsimony (i.e. classical cladists) counter that model-based methods also fail to be "statistically consistent" when an inappropriate model generates a tree that deviates from the true evolutionary history.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] They argue that for real data the true history is unknowable, making *any* method potentially inconsistent with no way to know.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Cladists therefore conclude that statistical inconsistency is purely metaphysical concern, outside the realm of empirical testing.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Another complication with maximum parsimony, and other optimality-criterion based phylogenetic methods, is that finding the shortest tree is an NP-hard problem.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The only currently available, efficient way of obtaining a solution, given an arbitrarily large set of taxa, is by using heuristic methods which do not guarantee that the shortest tree will be recovered.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] These methods employ hill-climbing algorithms to progressively approach the best tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, it has been shown that there can be "tree islands" of suboptimal solutions, and the analysis can become trapped in these local optima.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Thus, complex, flexible heuristics are required to ensure that tree space has been adequately explored.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Several heuristics are available, including nearest neighbor interchange (NNI), tree bisection reconnection (TBR), and the parsimony ratchet.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It has been asserted that a major problem, especially for paleontology, is that maximum parsimony assumes that the only way two species can share the same nucleotide at the same position is if they are genetically related.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This asserts that phylogenetic applications of parsimony assume that all similarity is homologous (other interpretations, such as the assertion that two organisms might *not* be related at all, are nonsensical).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is emphatically not the case: as with any form of character-based phylogeny estimation, parsimony is used to test the homologous nature of similarities by finding the phylogenetic tree which best accounts for all of the similarities.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It is often stated that parsimony is not relevant to phylogenetic inference because "evolution is not parsimonious." In most cases, there is no explicit alternative proposed; if no alternative is available, any statistical method is preferable to none at all.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Additionally, it is not clear what would be meant if the statement "evolution is parsimonious" were in fact true.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This could be taken to mean that more character changes may have occurred historically than are predicted using the parsimony criterion.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Because parsimony phylogeny estimation reconstructs the minimum number of changes necessary to explain a tree, this is quite possible.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] However, it has been shown through simulation studies, testing with known in vitro viral phylogenies, and congruence with other methods, that the accuracy of parsimony is in most cases not compromised by this.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Parsimony analysis uses the number of character changes on trees to choose the best tree, but it does not require that exactly that many changes, and no more, produced the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As long as the changes that have not been accounted for are randomly distributed over the tree (a reasonable null expectation), the result should not be biased.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In practice, the technique is robust: maximum parsimony exhibits minimal bias as a result of choosing the tree with the fewest changes.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] An analogy can be drawn with choosing among contractors based on their initial (nonbinding) estimate of the cost of a job.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The actual finished cost is very likely to be higher than the estimate.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Despite this, choosing the contractor who furnished the lowest estimate should theoretically result in the lowest final project cost.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is because, in the absence of other data, we would assume that all of the relevant contractors have the same risk of cost overruns.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In practice, of course, unscrupulous business practices may bias this result; in phylogenetics, too, some particular phylogenetic problems (for example, long branch attraction, described above) may potentially bias results.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In both cases, however, there is no way to tell if the result is going to be biased, or the degree to which it will be biased, based on the estimate itself.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] With parsimony too, there is no way to tell that the data are positively misleading, without comparison to other evidence.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Parsimony is often characterized as implicitly adopting the position that evolutionary change is rare, or that homoplasy (convergence and reversal) is minimal in evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This is not entirely true: parsimony minimizes the number of convergences and reversals that are assumed by the preferred tree, but this may result in a relatively large number of such homoplastic events.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] It would be more appropriate to say that parsimony assumes only the minimum amount of change implied by the data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] As above, this does not require that these were the only changes that occurred; it simply does not infer changes for which there is no evidence.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Recent simulation studies suggest that parsimony may be less accurate than trees built using Bayesian approaches for morphological data, potentially due to overprecision, although this has been disputed.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Also, analyses of 38 molecular and 86 morphological empirical datasets have shown that the common mechanism assumed by the evolutionary models used in model-based phylogenetics apply to most molecular, but few morphological datasets.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] This finding validates the use of model-based phylogenetics for molecular data, but suggests that for morphological data, parsimony remains advantageous, at least until more sophisticated models become available for phenotypic data.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There are several other methods for inferring phylogenies based on discrete character data, including maximum likelihood and Bayesian inference.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Each offers potential advantages and disadvantages.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In practice, these methods tend to favor trees that are very similar to the most parsimonious tree(s) for the same dataset; however, they allow for complex modelling of evolutionary processes, and as classes of methods are statistically consistent and are not susceptible to long-branch attraction.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Note, however, that the performance of likelihood and Bayesian methods are dependent on the quality of the particular model of evolution employed; an incorrect model can produce a biased result - just like parsimony.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] In addition, they are still quite computationally slow relative to parsimony methods, sometimes requiring weeks to run large datasets.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Most of these methods have particularly avid proponents and detractors; parsimony especially has been advocated as philosophically superior (most notably by ardent cladists).
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] One area where parsimony still holds much sway is in the analysis of morphological data, because—until recently—stochastic models of character change were not available for non-molecular data, and they are still not widely implemented.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Parsimony has also recently been shown to be more likely to recover the true tree in the face of profound changes in evolutionary ("model") parameters (e.g., the rate of evolutionary change) within a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Distance matrices can also be used to generate phylogenetic trees.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Non-parametric distance methods were originally applied to phenetic data using a matrix of pairwise distances and reconciled to produce a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] The distance matrix can come from a number of different sources, including immunological distance, morphometric analysis, and genetic distances.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] For phylogenetic character data, raw distance values can be calculated by simply counting the number of pairwise differences in character states (Manhattan distance) or by applying a model of evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Notably, distance methods also allow use of data that may not be easily converted to character data, such as DNA-DNA hybridization assays.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Today, distance-based methods are often frowned upon because phylogenetically-informative data can be lost when converting characters to distances.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] There are a number of distance-matrix methods and optimality criteria, of which the **minimum evolution** criterion is most closely related to maximum parsimony.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] From among the distance methods, there exists a phylogenetic estimation criterion, known as Minimum evolution (ME), that shares with maximum-parsimony the aspect of searching for the phylogeny that has the shortest total sum of branch lengths.
[src:phylogenetics/maximum-parsimony-phylogenetics] Rzhetsky and Nei's results set the ME criterion free from the Occam's razor principle and confer it a solid theoretical and quantitative basis.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The **molecular clock** is a figurative term for a technique that uses the mutation rate of biomolecules to deduce the time in prehistory when two or more life forms diverged.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The biomolecular data used for such calculations are usually nucleotide sequences for DNA, RNA, or amino acid sequences for proteins.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The notion of the existence of a so-called "molecular clock" was first attributed to Émile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling who, in 1962, noticed that the number of amino acid differences in hemoglobin between different lineages changes roughly linearly with time, as estimated from fossil evidence.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] They generalized this observation to assert that the rate of evolutionary change of any specified protein was approximately constant over time and over different lineages (known as the **molecular clock hypothesis**).
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] If this is correct, the cytochrome c of all mammals should be equally different from the cytochrome c of all birds.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Since fish diverges from the main stem of vertebrate evolution earlier than either birds or mammals, the cytochrome c of both mammals and birds should be equally different from the cytochrome c of fish.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Similarly, all vertebrate cytochrome c should be equally different from the yeast protein." For example, the difference between the cytochrome c of a carp and a frog, turtle, chicken, rabbit, and horse is a very constant 13% to 14%.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Similarly, the difference between the cytochrome c of a bacterium and yeast, wheat, moth, tuna, pigeon, and horse ranges from 64% to 69%.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Together with the work of Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling, the genetic equidistance result led directly to the formal postulation of the molecular clock hypothesis in the early 1960s.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Similarly, Vincent Sarich and Allan Wilson in 1967 demonstrated that molecular differences among modern primates in albumin proteins showed that approximately constant rates of change had occurred in all the lineages they assessed.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This method is known as the relative rate test.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Sarich and Wilson's paper reported, for example, that human (*Homo sapiens*) and chimpanzee (*Pan troglodytes*) albumin immunological cross-reactions suggested they were about equally different from Ceboidea (New World Monkey) species (within experimental error).
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This meant that they had both accumulated approximately equal changes in albumin since their shared common ancestor.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This pattern was also found for all the primate comparisons they tested.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] When calibrated with the few well-documented fossil branch points (such as the lack of primate fossils of modern aspect found before the K-T boundary), this led Sarich and Wilson to argue that the human-chimp divergence probably occurred only about 4–6 million years ago.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The observation of a clock-like rate of molecular change was originally purely phenomenological.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Later, the work of Motoo Kimura developed the neutral theory of molecular evolution, which predicted a molecular clock.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Let there be N individuals, and to keep this calculation simple, let the individuals be haploid (i.e. have one copy of each gene).
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Let the rate of neutral mutations (i.e. mutations with no effect on fitness) in a new individual be $\mu$ .
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The probability that this new mutation will become fixed in the population is then 1/N, since each copy of the gene is as good as any other.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Every generation, each individual can have new mutations, so there are $\mu$ N new neutral mutations in the population as a whole.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] That means that each generation, $\mu$ new neutral mutations will become fixed.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] If most changes seen during molecular evolution are neutral, then fixations in a population will accumulate at a clock-rate that is equal to the rate of neutral mutations in an individual.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] To use molecular clocks to estimate divergence times, molecular clocks need to be "calibrated".
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This is because molecular data alone does not contain any information on absolute times.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] For viral phylogenetics and ancient DNA studies—two areas of evolutionary biology where it is possible to sample sequences over an evolutionary timescale—the dates of the intermediate samples can be used to calibrate the molecular clock.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] However, most phylogenies require that the molecular clock be calibrated using independent evidence about dates, such as the fossil record.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] There are two general methods for calibrating the molecular clock using fossils: node calibration and tip calibration.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Sometimes referred to as node dating, node calibration is a method for time-scaling phylogenetic trees by specifying time constraints for one or more nodes in the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Early methods of clock calibration only used a single fossil constraint (e.g. non-parametric rate smoothing), but newer methods (BEAST and r8s) allow for the use of multiple fossils to calibrate molecular clocks.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The oldest fossil of a clade is used to constrain the minimum possible age for the node representing the most recent common ancestor of the clade.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] However, due to incomplete fossil preservation and other factors, clades are typically older than their oldest fossils.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] In order to account for this, nodes are allowed to be older than the minimum constraint in node calibration analyses.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] However, determining how much older the node is allowed to be is challenging.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] There are a number of strategies for deriving the maximum bound for the age of a clade including those based on birth-death models, fossil stratigraphic distribution analyses, or taphonomic controls.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Alternatively, instead of a maximum and a minimum, a probability density can be used to represent the uncertainty about the age of the clade.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] These calibration densities can take the shape of standard probability densities (e.g. normal, lognormal, exponential, gamma) that can be used to express the uncertainty associated with divergence time estimates.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Determining the shape and parameters of the probability distribution is not trivial, but there are methods that use not only the oldest fossil but a larger sample of the fossil record of clades to estimate calibration densities empirically.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Studies have shown that increasing the number of fossil constraints increases the accuracy of divergence time estimation.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Sometimes referred to as tip dating, tip calibration is a method of molecular clock calibration in which fossils are treated as taxa and placed on the tips of the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This is achieved by creating a matrix that includes a molecular dataset for the extant taxa along with a morphological dataset for both the extinct and the extant taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Unlike node calibration, this method reconstructs the tree topology and places the fossils simultaneously.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Molecular and morphological models work together simultaneously, allowing morphology to inform the placement of fossils.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Tip calibration makes use of all relevant fossil taxa during clock calibration, rather than relying on only the oldest fossil of each clade.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This method does not rely on the interpretation of negative evidence to infer maximum clade ages.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Demographic changes in populations can be detected as fluctuations in historical coalescent effective population size from a sample of extant genetic variation in the population using coalescent theory.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Ancient population expansions that are well documented and dated in the geological record can be used to calibrate a rate of molecular evolution in a manner similar to node calibration.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] However, instead of calibrating from the known age of a node, expansion calibration uses a two-epoch model of constant population size followed by population growth, with the time of transition between epochs being the parameter of interest for calibration.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Expansion calibration works at shorter, intraspecific timescales in comparison to node calibration, because expansions can only be detected after the most recent common ancestor of the species in question.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This approach to tip calibration goes a step further by simultaneously estimating fossil placement, topology, and the evolutionary timescale.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] In this method, the age of a fossil can inform its phylogenetic position in addition to morphology.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] By allowing all aspects of tree reconstruction to occur simultaneously, the risk of biased results is decreased.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This approach has been improved upon by pairing it with different models.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] One current method of molecular clock calibration is total evidence dating paired with the fossilized birth-death (FBD) model and a model of morphological evolution.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The FBD model is novel in that it allows for "sampled ancestors", which are fossil taxa that are the direct ancestor of a living taxon or lineage.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This allows fossils to be placed on a branch above an extant organism, rather than being confined to the tips.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Bayesian methods can provide more appropriate estimates of divergence times, especially if large datasets—such as those yielded by phylogenomics—are employed.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Sometimes only a single divergence date can be estimated from fossils, with all other dates inferred from that.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Other sets of species have abundant fossils available, allowing the hypothesis of constant divergence rates to be tested.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] DNA sequences experiencing low levels of negative selection showed divergence rates of 0.7–0.8% per Myr in bacteria, mammals, invertebrates, and plants.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] In the same study, genomic regions experiencing very high negative or purifying selection (encoding rRNA) were considerably slower (1% per 50 Myr).
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] In addition to such variation in rate with genomic position, since the early 1990s variation among taxa has proven fertile ground for research too, even over comparatively short periods of evolutionary time (for example mockingbirds).
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Tube-nosed seabirds have molecular clocks that on average run at half speed of many other birds, possibly due to long generation times, and many turtles have a molecular clock running at one-eighth the speed it does in small mammals, or even slower.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Effects of small population size are also likely to confound molecular clock analyses.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Ayala have more fundamentally challenged the molecular clock hypothesis.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Molecular clock users have developed workaround solutions using a number of statistical approaches including maximum likelihood techniques and later Bayesian modeling.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] In particular, models that take into account rate variation across lineages have been proposed in order to obtain better estimates of divergence times.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] It must be remembered that divergence dates inferred using a molecular clock are based on statistical inference and not on direct evidence.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The molecular clock runs into particular challenges at very short and very long timescales.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] At long timescales, the problem is saturation.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] When enough time has passed, many sites have undergone more than one change, but it is impossible to detect more than one.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] This means that the observed number of changes is no longer linear with time, but instead flattens out.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Even at intermediate genetic distances, with phylogenetic data still sufficient to estimate topology, signal for the overall scale of the tree can be weak under complex likelihood models, leading to highly uncertain molecular clock estimates.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] At very short time scales, many differences between samples do not represent fixation of different sequences in the different populations.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Instead, they represent alternative alleles that were both present as part of a polymorphism in the common ancestor.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The inclusion of differences that have not yet become fixed leads to a potentially dramatic inflation of the apparent rate of the molecular clock at very short timescales.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] The molecular clock technique is an important tool in molecular systematics, macroevolution, and phylogenetic comparative methods.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Estimation of the dates of phylogenetic events, including those not documented by fossils, such as the divergences between living taxa has allowed the study of macroevolutionary processes in organisms that had limited fossil records.
[src:phylogenetics/molecular-clock] Phylogenetic comparative methods rely heavily on calibrated phylogenies.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] In bioinformatics, **neighbor joining** is a bottom-up (agglomerative) clustering method for the creation of phylogenetic trees, created by Naruya Saitou and Masatoshi Nei in 1987.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Usually based on DNA or protein sequence data, the algorithm requires knowledge of the distance between each pair of taxa (e.g., species or sequences) to create the phylogenetic tree.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Neighbor joining takes a distance matrix, which specifies the distance between each pair of taxa, as input.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Find the pair of distinct taxa i and j (i.e. with $i\neq j$ ) for which $Q(i,j)$ is smallest.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Make a new node that joins the taxa i and j, and connect the new node to the central node.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] For example, in part (B) of the figure at right, node u is created to join f and g.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Calculate the distance from each of the taxa in the pair to this new node.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Calculate the distance from each of the taxa outside of this pair to the new node.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Start the algorithm again, replacing the pair of joined neighbors with the new node and using the distances calculated in the previous step.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] where $d(i,j)$ is the distance between taxa i and j .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Taxa f and g are the paired taxa and u is the newly created node.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The branches joining f and u and g and u , and their lengths, $\delta (f,u)$ and $\delta (g,u)$ are part of the tree which is gradually being created; they neither affect nor are affected by later neighbor-joining steps.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] where u is the new node, k is the node which we want to calculate the distance to and f and g are the members of the pair just joined.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Neighbor joining on a set of n taxa requires $n-3$ iterations.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] At each step one has to build and search a Q matrix.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Initially the Q matrix is size $n\times n$ , then the next step it is $(n-1)\times (n-1)$ , etc.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Implementing this in a straightforward way leads to an algorithm with a time complexity of $O(n^{3})$ ; implementations exist which use heuristics to do much better than this on average.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] We calculate the $Q_{1}$ values by equation (**1**).
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] This is the smallest value of $Q_{1}$ , so we join elements a and b .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] We then proceed to update the initial distance matrix D into a new distance matrix $D_{1}$ (see below), reduced in size by one row and one column because of the joining of a with b into their neighbor u .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Using equation (**3**) above, we compute the distance from u to each of the other nodes besides a and b .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Bold values in $D_{1}$ correspond to the newly calculated distances, whereas italicized values are not affected by the matrix update as they correspond to distances between elements not involved in the first joining of taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] We may choose either to join u and c , or to join d and e ; both pairs have the minimal $Q_{2}$ value of $-28$ , and either choice leads to the same result.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] For concreteness, let us join u and c and call the new node v .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The joining of the elements and the branch length calculation help drawing the neighbor joining tree as shown in the figure.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The tree topology is fully resolved at this point.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] However, for clarity, we can calculate the $Q_{3}$ matrix.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] For concreteness, let us join v and d and call the last node w .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The neighbor joining tree is now complete, as shown in the figure.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] This example represents an idealized case: note that if we move from any taxon to any other along the branches of the tree, and sum the lengths of the branches traversed, the result is equal to the distance between those taxa in the input distance matrix.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] For example, going from d to b we have $2+2+3+3=10$ .
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] A distance matrix whose distances agree in this way with some tree is said to be 'additive', a property which is rare in practice.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Given an additive distance matrix as input, neighbor joining is guaranteed to find the tree whose distances between taxa agree with it.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Neighbor joining may be viewed as a greedy heuristic for the balanced minimum evolution (BME) criterion.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] For each topology, BME defines the tree length (sum of branch lengths) to be a particular weighted sum of the distances in the distance matrix, with the weights depending on the topology.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The BME optimal topology is the one which minimizes this tree length.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] NJ at each step greedily joins that pair of taxa which will give the greatest decrease in the estimated tree length.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] This procedure does not guarantee to find the optimum for the BME criterion, although it often does and is usually quite close.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The main virtue of NJ is that it is fast as compared to least squares, maximum parsimony and maximum likelihood methods.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] This makes it practical for analyzing large data sets (hundreds or thousands of taxa) and for bootstrapping, for which purposes other means of analysis (e.g. maximum parsimony, maximum likelihood) may be computationally prohibitive.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Neighbor joining has the property that if the input distance matrix is correct, then the output tree will be correct.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Furthermore, the correctness of the output tree topology is guaranteed as long as the distance matrix is 'nearly additive', specifically if each entry in the distance matrix differs from the true distance by less than half of the shortest branch length in the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] In practice the distance matrix rarely satisfies this condition, but neighbor joining often constructs the correct tree topology anyway.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] The correctness of neighbor joining for nearly additive distance matrices implies that it is statistically consistent under many models of evolution; given data of sufficient length, neighbor joining will reconstruct the true tree with high probability.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Compared with UPGMA and WPGMA, neighbor joining has the advantage that it does not assume all lineages evolve at the same rate (molecular clock hypothesis).
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Nevertheless, neighbor joining has been largely superseded by phylogenetic methods that do not rely on distance measures and offer superior accuracy under most conditions.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Neighbor joining has the undesirable feature that it often assigns negative lengths to some of the branches.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] There are many programs available implementing neighbor joining.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] Among implementations of *canonical* NJ (i.e. using the classical NJ optimisation criteria, therefore giving the same results), RapidNJ (started 2003, major update in 2011, still updated in 2023) and NINJA (started 2009, last update 2013) are considered state-of-the-art.
[src:phylogenetics/neighbor-joining] They have typical run times proportional to approximately the square of the number of taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A **phylogenetic tree** or **phylogeny** is a graphical representation which shows the evolutionary history between a set of species or taxa during a specific time.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] In other words, it is a branching diagram or a tree showing the evolutionary relationships among various biological species or other entities based upon similarities and differences in their physical or genetic characteristics.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] In evolutionary biology, all life on Earth is theoretically part of a single phylogenetic tree, indicating common ancestry.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetics is the study of phylogenetic trees.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The main challenge is to find a phylogenetic tree representing optimal evolutionary ancestry between a set of species or taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Computational phylogenetics (also phylogeny inference) focuses on the algorithms involved in finding optimal phylogenetic tree in the phylogenetic landscape.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees may be rooted or unrooted.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] In a *rooted* phylogenetic tree, each node with descendants represents the inferred most recent common ancestor of those descendants, and the edge lengths in some trees may be interpreted as time estimates.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Internal nodes are generally called hypothetical taxonomic units, as they cannot be directly observed.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Trees are useful in fields of biology such as bioinformatics, systematics, and phylogenetics.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] *Unrooted* trees illustrate only the relatedness of the leaf nodes and do not require the ancestral root to be known or inferred.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The idea of a tree of life arose from ancient notions of a ladder-like progression from lower into higher forms of life (such as in the Great Chain of Being).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Early representations of "branching" phylogenetic trees include a "paleontological chart" showing the geological relationships among plants and animals in the book *Elementary Geology*, by Edward Hitchcock (first edition: 1840).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Charles Darwin featured a diagrammatic evolutionary "tree" in his 1859 book *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Over a century later, evolutionary biologists still use tree diagrams to depict evolution because such diagrams effectively convey the concept that speciation occurs through the adaptive and semirandom splitting of lineages.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The term *phylogenetic*, or *phylogeny*, derives from the two ancient greek words φῦλον (*phûlon*), meaning "race, lineage", and γένεσις (*génesis*), meaning "origin, source".
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A rooted phylogenetic tree (see two graphics at top) is a directed tree with a unique node — the root — corresponding to the (usually imputed) most recent common ancestor of all the entities at the leaves of the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The root node does not have a parent node, but serves as the parent of all other nodes in the tree.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The root is therefore a node of degree 2, while other internal nodes have a minimum degree of 3 (where "degree" here refers to the total number of incoming and outgoing edges).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The most common method for rooting trees is the use of an uncontroversial outgroup—close enough to allow inference from trait data or molecular sequencing, but far enough to be a clear outgroup.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Another method is midpoint rooting, or a tree can also be rooted by using a non-stationary substitution model.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Unrooted trees illustrate the relatedness of the leaf nodes without making assumptions about ancestry.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] They do not require the ancestral root to be known or inferred.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Rooted trees can be generated from unrooted ones by inserting a root.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Inferring the root of an unrooted tree requires some means of identifying ancestry.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Both rooted and unrooted trees can be either bifurcating or multifurcating.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A rooted bifurcating tree has exactly two descendants arising from each interior node (that is, it forms a binary tree), and an unrooted bifurcating tree takes the form of an unrooted binary tree, a free tree with exactly three neighbors at each internal node.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] In contrast, a rooted multifurcating tree may have more than two children at some nodes and an unrooted multifurcating tree may have more than three neighbors at some nodes.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Both rooted and unrooted trees can be either labeled or unlabeled.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A labeled tree has specific values assigned to its leaves, while an unlabeled tree, sometimes called a tree shape, defines a topology only.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Some sequence-based trees built from a small genomic locus, such as Phylotree, feature internal nodes labeled with inferred ancestral haplotypes.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The number of possible trees for a given number of leaf nodes depends on the specific type of tree, but there are always more labeled than unlabeled trees, more multifurcating than bifurcating trees, and more rooted than unrooted trees.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The last distinction is the most biologically relevant; it arises because there are many places on an unrooted tree to put the root.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Among labeled bifurcating trees, the number of unrooted trees with n leaves is equal to the number of rooted trees with $n-1$ leaves.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The number of rooted trees grows quickly as a function of the number of tips.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] For 10 tips, there are more than $34\times 10^{6}$ possible bifurcating trees, and the number of multifurcating trees rises faster, with ca.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] 7 times as many of the latter as of the former.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A dendrogram is a general name for a tree, whether phylogenetic or not, and hence also for the diagrammatic representation of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A cladogram only represents a branching pattern; i.e., its branch lengths do not represent time or relative amount of character change, and its internal nodes do not represent ancestors.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A phylogram is a phylogenetic tree that has branch lengths proportional to the amount of character change.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A chronogram is a phylogenetic tree that explicitly represents time through its branch lengths.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A Dahlgrenogram is a diagram representing a cross section of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A phylogenetic network is not strictly speaking a tree, but rather a more general graph, or a directed acyclic graph in the case of rooted networks.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] They are used to overcome some of the limitations inherent to trees.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A spindle diagram, or bubble diagram, is often called a romerogram, after its popularisation by the American palaeontologist Alfred Romer.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] It represents taxonomic diversity (horizontal width) against geological time (vertical axis) in order to reflect the variation of abundance of various taxa through time.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] A spindle diagram is not an evolutionary tree: the taxonomic spindles obscure the actual relationships of the parent taxon to the daughter taxon and have the disadvantage of involving the paraphyly of the parental group.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] This type of diagram is no longer used in the form originally proposed.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Darwin also mentioned that the *coral* may be a more suitable metaphor than the *tree*.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Indeed, phylogenetic corals are useful for portraying past and present life, and they have some advantages over trees (anastomoses allowed, etc.).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees composed with a nontrivial number of input sequences are constructed using computational phylogenetics methods.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Distance-matrix methods such as neighbor-joining or UPGMA, which calculate genetic distance from multiple sequence alignments, are simplest to implement, but do not invoke an evolutionary model.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Many sequence alignment methods such as ClustalW also create trees by using the simpler algorithms (i.e. those based on distance) of tree construction.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Maximum parsimony is another simple method of estimating phylogenetic trees, but implies an implicit model of evolution (i.e. parsimony).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] More advanced methods use the optimality criterion of maximum likelihood, often within a Bayesian framework, and apply an explicit model of evolution to phylogenetic tree estimation.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Identifying the optimal tree using many of these techniques is NP-hard, so heuristic search and optimization methods are used in combination with tree-scoring functions to identify a reasonably good tree that fits the data.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Tree-building techniques have also gained the attention of mathematicians.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Trees can be encoded in a number of different formats, all of which must represent the nested structure of a tree.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] They may or may not encode branch lengths and other features.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Standardized formats are critical for distributing and sharing trees without relying on graphics output that is hard to import into existing software.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Although phylogenetic trees produced on the basis of sequenced genes or genomic data in different species can provide evolutionary insight, these analyses have important limitations.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Most importantly, the trees that they generate are not necessarily correct – they do not necessarily accurately represent the evolutionary history of the included taxa.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] As with any scientific result, they are subject to falsification by further study (e.g., gathering of additional data, analyzing the existing data with improved methods).
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The data on which they are based may be noisy; the analysis can be confounded by genetic recombination, horizontal gene transfer, hybridisation between species that were not nearest neighbors on the tree before hybridisation takes place, and conserved sequences.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] This is most true of genetic material that is subject to lateral gene transfer and recombination, where different haplotype blocks can have different histories.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] In these types of analysis, the output tree of a phylogenetic analysis of a single gene is an estimate of the gene's phylogeny (i.e. a gene tree) and not the phylogeny of the taxa (i.e. species tree) from which these characters were sampled, though ideally, both should be very close.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] When extinct species are included as terminal nodes in an analysis (rather than, for example, to constrain internal nodes), they are considered not to represent direct ancestors of any extant species.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Extinct species do not typically contain high-quality DNA.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] The range of useful DNA materials has expanded with advances in extraction and sequencing technologies.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Development of technologies able to infer sequences from smaller fragments, or from spatial patterns of DNA degradation products, would further expand the range of DNA considered useful.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees can also be inferred from a range of other data types, including morphology, the presence or absence of particular types of genes, insertion and deletion events – and any other observation thought to contain an evolutionary signal.
[src:phylogenetics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic networks are used when bifurcating trees are not suitable, due to these complications which suggest a more reticulate evolutionary history of the organisms sampled.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Note that the unweighted term indicates that all distances contribute equally to each average that is computed and does not refer to the math by which it is achieved.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Thus the simple averaging in WPGMA produces a weighted result and the proportional averaging in UPGMA produces an unweighted result (*see the working example*).
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] The UPGMA algorithm constructs a rooted tree (dendrogram) that reflects the structure present in a pairwise similarity matrix (or a dissimilarity matrix).
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] At each step, the nearest two clusters are combined into a higher-level cluster.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] The UPGMA algorithm produces rooted dendrograms and requires a constant-rate assumption - that is, it assumes an ultrametric tree in which the distances from the root to every branch tip are equal.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] When the tips are molecular data (*i.e.*, DNA, RNA and protein) sampled at the same time, the ultrametricity assumption becomes equivalent to assuming a molecular clock.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] This working example is based on a JC69 genetic distance matrix computed from the 5S ribosomal RNA sequence alignment of five bacteria: *Bacillus subtilis* ( a ), *Bacillus stearothermophilus* ( b ), *Lactobacillus viridescens* ( c ), *Acholeplasma modicum* ( d ), and *Micrococcus luteus* ( e ).
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] In this example, $D_{1}(a,b)=17$ is the smallest value of $D_{1}$ , so we join elements a and b .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Let u denote the node to which a and b are now connected.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Setting $\delta (a,u)=\delta (b,u)=D_{1}(a,b)/2$ ensures that elements a and b are equidistant from u .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] This corresponds to the expectation of the ultrametricity hypothesis.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] We then proceed to update the initial distance matrix $D_{1}$ into a new distance matrix $D_{2}$ (see below), reduced in size by one row and one column because of the clustering of a with b .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Italicized values in $D_{2}$ are not affected by the matrix update as they correspond to distances between elements not involved in the first cluster.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Let v denote the node to which $(a,b)$ and e are now connected.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] We then proceed to update $D_{2}$ into a new distance matrix $D_{3}$ (see below), reduced in size by one row and one column because of the clustering of $(a,b)$ with e .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Thanks to this proportional average, the calculation of this new distance accounts for the larger size of the $(a,b)$ cluster (two elements) with respect to e (one element).
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Proportional averaging therefore gives equal weight to the initial distances of matrix $D_{1}$ .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] This is the reason why the method is *unweighted*, not with respect to the mathematical procedure but with respect to the initial distances.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] We again reiterate the three previous steps, starting from the updated distance matrix $D_{3}$ .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Here, $D_{3}(c,d)=28$ is the smallest value of $D_{3}$ , so we join elements c and d .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Let w denote the node to which c and d are now connected.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Let r denote the (root) node to which $((a,b),e)$ and $(c,d)$ are now connected.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] The dendrogram is therefore rooted by r , its deepest node.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Alternative linkage schemes include single linkage clustering, complete linkage clustering, and WPGMA average linkage clustering.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Implementing a different linkage is simply a matter of using a different formula to calculate inter-cluster distances during the distance matrix update steps of the above algorithm.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Complete linkage tends to find compact clusters of approximately equal diameters.
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] A trivial implementation of the algorithm to construct the UPGMA tree has $O(n^{3})$ time complexity, and using a heap for each cluster to keep its distances from other cluster reduces its time to $O(n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:phylogenetics/upgma] Fionn Murtagh presented an $O(n^{2})$ time and space algorithm.
